22/06/2007
The World Bank approved a 22.3m-euro financing package meant to aid forestry, agriculture and rural development, urban infrastructure and services in Bosnia and Herzegovina. Out of the total, 4.5m euros will be provided by the Swedish International Development Co-operation Agency. The funds are being provided via soft loans, without interest and with a 25-year repayment period. 
*** 
The European Commission adopted a strategy for 2007-2009 EU financial assistance to the Balkans. In all, the EU will provide around 3.96 billion euros in funding to Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Macedonia, Montenegro, Serbia, Kosovo and Turkey. 
 *** 
Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) Prime Minister Nikola Spiric urged Malaysian companies Thursday (June 21st) to invest in BiH, particularly in Srebrenica. His call came during talks in Sarajevo with Malaysian counterpart Datuk Seri Abdullah Ahmad Badawi. During the visit, the two countries signed an agreement on avoidance of double taxation. 
*** 
Bulgaria's GDP growth accelerated to 6.2% year-on-year in the first quarter of 2007, up from 5.6% in the same period last year, according to the latest statistical data. The figure exceeds the government target of 6% annual growth. GDP growth has been driven mainly by strong foreign investments. 
 *** 
Romania's leading oil and gas producer, Petrom, said it will launch a 500m-euro project to build a gas-fired electricity plant. The facility will have a capacity of 860 MW and is expected to become operational in three years. 
